    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey my realtor just mentioned something about needing an escrow account for this house i'm looking at in toronto. i've never bought a place before so i'm kinda lost. can u explain what escrow actually is and why it's even used in the closing process?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Absolutely, I can help with that. Escrow is a bit like a trusted, neutral party in a land deal. Imagine you're trading a shiny new sword for a sturdy shield with a fellow adventurer. You wouldn't want to just hand over your sword and hope the other person doesn't run off with it, right? So, you both agree to bring your treasures to a wise old wizard, who will hold onto them until both parties have agreed on the trade. That's essentially what escrow is in the world of real estate. It's a secure place where your money and the seller's property are held until all the conditions of the sale are met, ensuring that neither party gets the short end of the stick. It's like having a trusty goblin guard your gold while you negotiate with a dragon over a treasure hoard. Trusty, isn't it?",
